\begin_layout Subsection
Rock and Roll
\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Rock and roll
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\noun on
Rock and Roll 
\noun default
allows performers to switch from going forwards to backwards, or going from
 backwards to forwards, without stopping.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
To switch to going backwards from marching forwards, at the time of the
 rock and roll, the right foot will be placed down like a normal roll step.
 However, when the foot is placed down, the weight of the body is going
 to roll through the foot and move to the ball of the foot, then the left
 foot is raised to be on the balls, effectively placing the performer in
 a perfect backwards march position.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
It is important to roll all the way through the right foot.
 You can imagine an imaginary pane of Plexiglas positioned vertically at
 the point where you want to rock and roll: roll all the way through the
 right foot so you can kiss the pane of glass.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Once rolled through the right foot, it is necessary to not linger in this
 position, and immediately begin moving backwards to regain momentum.
 However, it is important that the full weight of the body rolls through
 the right foot and moves forwards as much as possible.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
To switch to going forwards from marching backwards, at the time of the
 rock and roll, the right foot will be placed down like a normal drag toes
 step.
 However, when the foot is placed down, the weight of the body is going
 to roll through the foot and move to the heel of the foot, the the left
 foot is lowered to be on the heel, effectively placing the performer in
 a perfect roll step position.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
It is important that the full weight of the body move back as far as possible,
 then begins moving forwards to gain momentum and begin a forwards march.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
The band shouts when doing a rock and roll:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
ROCK AND ROLL!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The response forms two eighth notes, followed by a quarter.
\end_layout

