\begin_layout Standard
Boxes are good for practicing flankings and roll stepping.
 While we practice those fundamentals, we can also practice traversing with
 
\noun on
Traverse Boxes
\noun default
.
 Traverse boxes are just normal boxes, while also traversing in one direction
 the whole time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The traverse direction is chosen arbitrarily, as long as the direction can
 be traversed to at the beginning (cannot traverse home sideline when facing
 away).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One side of the traverse box will be backwards marching, one side will be
 forwards marching, and two sides will be traversing.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
As mentioned in Subsection
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand vref
reference "traversing-never-backwards-at-90"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, performers will never march backwards when traversing at a 90°.
 They will forwards march while traversing the appropriate direction.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For example, if the band was facing field left, traversing to the home sideline,
 and doing a traverse box left:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The first edge of the box will be a forwards march while traversing home
 (upper body rotated right).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The band will then backwards flank and march backwards the second edge of
 the box.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The third edge of the box will be a forwards march while traversing home
 (upper body rotated left).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The final edge of the box will be a forwards march.
 The final step will return the feet to the initial direction ending the
 traverse box.
\end_layout

