\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Much of what is presented in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Price2017"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 has nothing to do with the topic of teaching a marching band, but Price's
 points of teaching are actually applicable and I will adapt what Price
 presents and apply it to teaching a marching band.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{Effective~teaching}=\text{Result}+\text{Practice}+\text{Clarity}+\text{Delivery}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's discuss each component of this sum and how it applies in context.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Result
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\noun on
Result
\noun default
 is the end product.
 It's the goal that you and the rest of the band want to achieve.
 That's why whenever you start teaching fundamentals, you want to state
 what that end goal is.
 Teaching the band a bunch of fundamentals without really telling them why
 you're teaching them them might not make a whole lot of sense in the mind
 of a freshman.
 You might explain why we learn and practice fundamentals, how they're used
 in the show, and what the show actually is! You absolutely have to paint
 this picture in the heads of the freshmen to begin the path.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Practice
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Before you begin teaching the band, you have to 
\noun on
Practice 
\noun default
teaching the fundamentals to someone else.
 Why? Let's imagine the scenario where you don't.
 It's day 1 of band camp.
 100 people are standing on the field in front of you and you have no idea
 what you are going to say.
 You're making words up on the spot, making a ton of mistakes, and confusing
 the freshmen.
 Practice before camp so you know specific details you want to point out,
 mistakes you want to avoid, and precise wording you want to say.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Clarity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote

\emph on
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Any fool can make something complicated.
 It takes a genius to make it simple.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 – Woodie Guthrie
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Much like previous statements, wording is key.
 If you can't properly state the thoughts you are trying to present, your
 presentation is going to go off key.
 You might start explaining something one way, then realize what you're
 explaining is incorrect, effectively wasting time.
 Plan and choose your words and thoughts carefully.
 Try to explain the most amount of information in the simplest and fewest
 words possible.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
